Looking at the `copyAttributes` method more carefully:

```java
private void copyAttributes(org.jsoup.nodes.Node source, Element el) {
    for (Attribute attribute : source.attributes()) {
        // valid xml attribute names are: ^[a-zA-Z_:][-a-zA-Z0-9_:.]
        String key = attribute.getKey().replaceAll("[^-a-zA-Z0-9_:.]", "");
            el.setAttribute(key, attribute.getValue());
    }
}
```

This method removes invalid characters but if the attribute name becomes empty after sanitization, calling `el.setAttribute(key, ...)` with an empty key would likely cause problems in W3C DOM.

Let me analyze what happens when the attribute name contains quotes. The HTML `<body style="color: red" \" name\">` creates attributes where one might have a key that's just `"` and another might be `name"`.

I should check if the attribute key is empty or invalid after sanitization and skip those attributes.

